Again for `cevalpoly`, setting `double tmp = b` before the loop, would require moving `tmp = b` to the end of the loop, and if we didn't want to set `tmp` one more time than needed, we'd need to stop the loop one early, and then put 

`C++
	b = std::fma(-s, a, coeffs[j]);
	a = std::fma(r, a, tmp);
```

after the loop, which just doesn't seem worth it. I don't ike setting `tmp = b` an extra time either, even though it probably has no real performance impact.
